Successfully implemented the Allergies exercise! All 50 tests pass.

## Solution

The `Allergies` class uses bitwise operations to efficiently determine allergies from a numeric score:

```javascript
const ALLERGENS = [
  { name: 'eggs', value: 1 },
  { name: 'peanuts', value: 2 },
  { name: 'shellfish', value: 4 },
  { name: 'strawberries', value: 8 },
  { name: 'tomatoes', value: 16 },
  { name: 'chocolate', value: 32 },
  { name: 'pollen', value: 64 },
  { name: 'cats', value: 128 },
];

export class Allergies {
  constructor(score) {
    this.score = score;
  }

  list() {
    return ALLERGENS.filter((allergen) => this.allergicTo(allergen.name)).map(
      (a) => a.name
    );
  }

  allergicTo(item) {
    const allergen = ALLERGENS.find((a) => a.name === item);
    if (!allergen) return false;
    return (this.score & allergen.value) !== 0;
  }
}
```

## How it works

- Each allergen has a value that's a power of 2 (1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128)
- The `allergicTo()` method uses bitwise AND (`&`) to check if the corresponding bit is set in the score
- The `list()` method filters all allergens to find which ones the person is allergic to
- Scores ≥ 256 are automatically ignored since none of our defined allergens have those bit values set (the `&` operation simply returns 0 for those bits)
